Task:

Given a set of data that covered the price of electricity in Sydney for the year 2013, and the maximum and minimum temperatures of each day, the task was to perform statistical analysis of the data. This includes trying to fit a model to the data and then using this model to predict the cost of electricity for the first week of 2014.

Initial actions:

After executing the file given to us alongside the task that formatted the data, I had to decide whether or not to include the clear outlier in the data, caused by an electrical storm. You can see this outlier in the plot below

I decided to discard the outlier and thus limit my model to only capture the cost of electricty on a day without extreme weather, thus sacrificing the model’s coverage of all situations for higher accuracy. I also added the temperature data and what weekday each day was to the AEMO data frame.All this is as below

AEMO$day <- weekdays(as.Date(AEMO$Date, '%d/%m/%Y'))
AEMO$maxtemp <- maxTemp
AEMO$mintemp <- minTemp
AEMO <- AEMO[-c(354),]
maxTemp <- maxTemp[-c(354)]
minTemp <- minTemp[-c(354)]

I then followed the examples from lecture 1 and checked the simple statistics for the price of the electricity, including a quantile-quantile plot to check for normality:

Although not perfect, it seems from the quantile-quantile that the temperature difference is close to being normally distributed, and from doing a linear model of max versus min temperature, there is strong significance in the model. From this (and due to time constraints) I am going to focus soley on the MaxTemp, and assume that the minimum temperature wouldn’t give me much more information.

Looking at this summary and graph now, we can see that the polynomial is actually of too higher degree: The statistical significance of the powers above 5 are minimal and we have a good example of the volatility of the model at the extremes, demonstrated at the higher temperatures. This leads us to think that a degree 5 polynomial would be the best fit:

This model seems to fit the data well, which seems to fit the data as we have taken the most significant factors from the degree 10 polynomial and ignored the insignificant factors. The ends of our model are much less volatile than previous, and although the model seems to counterintuitively rise at either end of our data, I think that is plausible when considering the context: As the temperature increases there is less need for heating, lights etc., giving the general downwards direction of the graph. However, as the temperature gets futher from the norm, people will consume electricity in the form of airconditioning and heating, adding to the demand and rising the price.

Splines

In addition to polynomial models, it is also worth looking at splines; the model may be more accurate if we split the data up with knots and model each section with a cubic. Following the examples form lecture 2 again:

From comparing the difference in the splines from having less degrees freedom, the lack of kinks in the former graph inidcates that it is probable more realistic.

So now we have our two optimal models; a quintic polynomial regression and a spline with degree freedom five; let’s compare them:

library("splines")
lmresult<-lm(AEMO$RRP~ns(maxTemp,df=5))
plot(maxTemp,AEMO$RRP, main='Spline with 5 degrees freedom versus quintic model')
points(maxTemp, lmresult$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(maxTemp), max(maxTemp), length.out=364)
lines(predpoints, predict(lmresult, data.frame(maxTemp=predpoints)), col='blue')

lmresult<-lm(AEMO$RRP~poly(maxTemp, degree=5))
points(maxTemp, lmresult$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(maxTemp), max(maxTemp), length.out=364)
lines(predpoints, predict(lmresult, data.frame(maxTemp=predpoints)), col='purple')

From this we can see that the two models are indistinguishable until around 27 degrees, where there is less data so the two models diverge. Taking the concept that the simpler models is often better, I would suggest that the spline model is the best model to use.

Does the day of the week have an affect on the price of electricity?

Let’s compare the price of electricity across the seven days of the week:

From this we can see that the weekend days have a slightly lower average than the others, so we now try to add a quintic model which takes into account the days of the week too:

lmresult<-lm(AEMO$RRP~AEMO$day + poly(maxTemp, degree=5))
summary(lmresult)

Predicting future values

First, for ease, I predict the price of electricty for the first week of the new year using the quintic polynomial regression mdel:

lmresult<-lm(AEMO$RRP~ poly(maxTemp, degree=5))
new.temps <- data.frame(maxTemp=c(20.5,22.3,21.0,20.1,20.8,19.6,18.3))
predict(lmresult, newdata=new.temps,interval='prediction')
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 53.38599 46.58369 60.18829
## 2 52.21708 45.41822 59.01595
## 3 52.97307 46.17272 59.77341
## 4 53.76820 46.96349 60.57291
## 5 53.12972 46.32872 59.93072
## 6 54.31235 47.50340 61.12129

Now we encorporate the days of the week to see if that makes a difference:

Daysofweek<- AEMO$day
lmresult<-lm(AEMO$RRP~ Daysofweek + poly(maxTemp, degree=5))
new.temps <- data.frame(maxTemp=c(20.5,22.3,21.0,20.1,20.8,19.6,18.3), Daysofweek=c("Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday" ))
predict(lmresult, newdata=new.temps,interval='prediction')
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 53.58622 47.04756 60.12487
## 2 52.59981 46.06348 59.13614
## 3 53.16472 46.63152 59.69791
## 4 52.62949 46.08746 59.17152
## 5 51.03330 44.49937 57.56723
## 6 55.67476 49.13291 62.21661
## 7 57.22617 50.66083 63.79151

We can see from comparing the two sets of predictions that the incorporation of the fact that the fifth day is Sunday noticably decreases the estimation of the cost of electricity for that day.
